SIMPLE: philosopher
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Philosopher
<hw>Phi*los"o*pher</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>philosophre</ets>, F. <ets>philosophe</ets>, L.
<ets>philosophus</ets>, Gr. <grk>filo`sofos</grk>; <grk>fi`los</grk>
loving + <grk>sofo`s</grk> wise. Cf. <er>Philosophy</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>One who philosophizes; one versed in, or devoted to,
philosophy.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Then certain <qex>philosophers</qex> of the Epicureans, and of the
Stoics, encountered him.</q> <rj><qau>Acts xvii. 18.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>One who reduces the principles of philosophy to
practice in the conduct of life; one who lives according to the rules of
practical wisdom; one who meets or regards all vicissitudes with
calmness.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>An alchemist.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Philosopher's stone</b></col>, <cd>an imaginary stone
which the alchemists formerly sought as the instrument of converting the
baser metals into gold.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Philosophical</ent>⟦br⟧
<ent>Philosophic</ent>⟦br⟧
